Here's how to handle it using MAUI's app lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**In your `NotePage.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "note_draft";

    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        // Restore draft on page load
        NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnAppearing()
    {
        base.OnAppearing();

        // Subscribe to lifecycle events
        App.Current.Windows[0].Backgrounding += OnBackgrounding;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Resuming += OnResuming;
    }

    protected override void OnDisappearing()
    {
        base.OnDisappearing();

        App.Current.Windows[0].Backgrounding -= OnBackgrounding;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Resuming -= OnResuming;
    }

    private void OnBackgrounding(object sender, BackgroundingEventArgs e)
    {
        // Save draft when app goes to background
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    private void OnResuming(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // Restore draft when app resumes
        NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);
    }

    // Call this when the user explicitly saves/discards
    public void ClearDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Preferences`** — simple key-value store that persists across sessions. Good for small text. For large content, use `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory` with file I/O instead.
- **`Backgrounding`** — fires when the app loses focus (home button, app switch).
- **`Resuming`** — fires when the app returns to foreground.
- **Unsubscribe** in `OnDisappearing` to avoid leaks.
- **Call `ClearDraft()`** after a deliberate save/discard so stale drafts don't reappear.
